# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 4. GIT WORKFLOW — MANDATORY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Repository: https://github.com/Bhargavi2212/Healthcart
Deploy:     https://healthcart-iota.vercel.app (Vercel, connected to main branch)
Database:   Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL — provision and configure from this repo only
            (see docs/AWS_SETUP.md). DATABASE_URL in .env.local + Vercel env vars.

This folder IS the entire HealthCart project. Not a subfolder of another monorepo.

Commit after EVERY completed step in PHASE_1.md, PHASE_2.md, or PHASE_3.md.
Not at the end of a phase. One step = one commit = one PROGRESS.md update.

Workflow after each step:
1. Complete the step and verify (per phase doc)
2. Stage only files changed for that step, plus PROGRESS.md
3. Commit with the message specified in the phase doc (or format below)
4. In PROGRESS.md: check the step Done column and add hash + message to Commit log
5. git push origin main (keeps Vercel in sync)

Commit format: <type>(<scope>): <description>

Types: feat, fix, chore, data, style, test, docs
Scopes: infra, schema, data, scoring, optimizer, ai, chat, ui, shop, basket, family, deploy, progress

Examples:
  chore(infra): initialize Next.js with Tailwind and Prisma
  data(usda): import USDA FoodData Central into Aurora
  feat(scoring): implement family health scoring algorithm
  feat(ai): build natural language context extraction with Gemini
  feat(shop): build product grid with dynamic health badges
  style(ui): implement design system color tokens
  docs(progress): mark phase 1 step 1.3 complete

Never commit: .env.local, credentials, API keys, Aurora passwords.

Update PROGRESS.md in the SAME commit as the step (not a separate commit).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 5. DATA SOURCES — USE REAL DATA
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

## 5.1 USDA FoodData Central
Primary source: https://fdc.nal.usda.gov/
Bulk download: https://fdc.nal.usda.gov/download-datasets.html
Download "Foundation Foods" and "SR Legacy" datasets (CSV/JSON). 300,000+ foods.
English names only — no Telugu/Hindi columns. Food codes are USDA NDB/FDC numbers.

Secondary source for branded products: Open Food Facts (https://world.openfoodfacts.org/)
Use for packaged/branded items not well covered in Foundation Foods.

Parse into NutritionLookup: foodCode, foodGroup, nameEn, energyKcal, proteinG,
totalFatG, carbsG, fiberG, sugarG, ironMg, calciumMg, vitaminAUg, vitaminCMg,
folateMg, potassiumMg, sodiumMg, saturatedFatG, glycemicIndex (nullable if missing).
nameHi and nameTe columns stay in schema but remain empty for US demo.

Action: Download, parse, write import script, load into Aurora NutritionLookup table.

## 5.2 Health Condition Rules
Sources: USDA Dietary Guidelines for Americans 2020-2025, American Heart Association
guidelines, WHO nutrition guidance. Same structure (condition → boost/limit/avoid).

Chronic conditions: diabetes, cholesterol, hypertension, anemia, thyroid (single
condition — not hypo/hyper split), obesity, pregnancy, celiac/gluten intolerance,
peanut allergy, lactose intolerance.

Temporary conditions: fever, cold, cough, stomach_upset, period_cramps,
post_surgery, fasting.

Each rule: condition, action (boost/limit/avoid), targetTag, scoreImpact, reason,
source (usda_dietary_guidelines, aha_guidelines, or published_literature),
autoExpireDays for temporary conditions.

Do NOT include: pcos, hypothyroid/hyperthyroid as separate conditions.

## 5.3 Dietary Tag Rules
Same auto-tag logic from nutritional data. Research thresholds from USDA RDA values
(not ICMR). Examples: iron_rich, high_fiber, low_glycemic, diabetic_friendly,
high_protein, vitamin_c_rich, low_calorie, high_sugar, high_sodium, calcium_rich,
folate_rich, easily_digestible, hydrating, gluten_free, dairy_free, peanut_free.

Categorical tags: vegetarian, easily_digestible, hydrating, light_meal, bbq_friendly.
Remove sattvic tag — not relevant for US demo.

## 5.4 Product Catalog
100+ real American grocery products. Prices in USD. nameTe optional (leave empty).

Categories:
- Vegetables: kale, spinach, broccoli, bell peppers, sweet potato, zucchini,
  avocado, tomato, carrots, celery, Brussels sprouts, asparagus, corn, green beans
- Fruits: blueberries, strawberries, bananas, apples, oranges, watermelon, grapes,
  lemons, peaches, mangoes
- Proteins: chicken breast, ground turkey, salmon, eggs, tofu, Greek yogurt,
  cottage cheese, black beans, lentils, chickpeas
- Grains: brown rice, quinoa, oats, whole wheat bread, whole wheat pasta, tortillas
- Dairy: milk (whole, 2%, almond, oat), cheese, butter, cream cheese
- Pantry: olive oil, peanut butter, almond butter, honey, marinara sauce, salsa,
  soy sauce, hot sauce (turmeric, cumin etc. as pantry items if needed — not a
  separate spice category)
- Snacks: hummus, trail mix, granola bars, dark chocolate, popcorn

Each product: nameEn, category, subcategory, price (USD), weight_options as variants,
usdaFoodCode FK to NutritionLookup, isSeasonal where applicable.

## 5.5 Product Images
Royalty-free images (Unsplash, Pexels, Pixabay) of American grocery products.
WebP format, max 400px width. Store in /public/products/. Named by slug:
kale.webp, spinach.webp, quinoa.webp.

Do NOT use placeholder data. Every product, price, and nutritional value must be real.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 6. DATABASE SCHEMA (Prisma)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Tables (keep it minimal — only what the AI engine needs):

## Family Management
- Family: id, name, createdAt
- FamilyMember: id, familyId, name, age, relation, dietType, conditions (String[]),
  allergies (String[]), heightCm, weightKg, isTemporary, startDate, endDate
- WeeklyContext: id, familyId, weekStart, rawMessage, extractedContext (JSON),
  cuisineMood, createdAt

## Nutrition Knowledge
- NutritionLookup: foodCode (PK — USDA NDB/FDC number), foodGroup, nameEn,
  nameHi (optional, empty), nameTe (optional, empty), energyKcal, proteinG,
  totalFatG, carbsG, fiberG, sugarG, ironMg, calciumMg, vitaminAUg, vitaminCMg,
  folateMg, potassiumMg, sodiumMg, saturatedFatG, glycemicIndex
- HealthConditionRule: id, condition, action, targetTag, scoreImpact, reason,
  source, autoExpireDays (nullable), isActive
- DietaryTagRule: id, tagName, nutrientColumn, operator, threshold, description

## Products
- Product: id, nameEn, nameTe (optional — not required), description, category,
  subcategory, imageUrl, isSeasonal, availableMonths (Int[]), usdaFoodCode (FK),
  isActive, createdAt
- ProductVariant: id, productId, weightValue, weightUnit, price, sku
- DietaryTag: id, productId, tag

## AI Output
- ProductScore, BasketRecommendation — unchanged from original design.

That's 11 tables. Schema identical; nameTe optional; ifctFoodCode renamed usdaFoodCode
in application code (or keep column name ifctFoodCode as FK alias — prefer usdaFoodCode
in Prisma for clarity).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 7. SCORING ENGINE — THE BRAIN
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Pure TypeScript. Zero external API calls. Deterministic.

Algorithm unchanged. Example products for US context:
- Kale scores high for anemia (iron) and cholesterol (fiber)
- Quinoa scores high (gluten-free, high protein, low glycemic)
- Products with gluten get "avoid" for celiac family members
- Peanut products get "avoid" for members with peanut allergy
- White bread scores low for pre-diabetic members (high glycemic)

CRITICAL RULES:
- Reasoning MUST use actual member names: "Good for Jake's peanut allergy — gluten-free"
  not "good for family member with allergy"
- Avoid badge wins for ANY member when hard-avoid rules match (safety first)
- Cuisine mood (BBQ, meal prep, keto-friendly) boosts but never overrides health constraints
- Engine never calls an LLM

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 8. QUANTITY LOGIC
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Research USDA Dietary Guidelines / DRI for Americans — not ICMR RDA.
Americans typically consume less vegetables per person than ICMR recommends for Indians;
derive base per-person weekly consumption from USDA sources.

Examples:
- Leafy greens: research USDA serving guidance per person per week
- Kale: if family needs iron and kale has ~2.7mg/100g, calculate meaningful contribution
- Shelf life: US grocery perishables (bagged salad 3-5 days, root veg full week)
- Snap to variants: 1.2 lb → snap to 1 lb or 2 lb package
- Budget: "keep it under $75" — reduce mood items first; show coverage tradeoff

Store in lib/quantities.ts as pure functions.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 9. AI CONVERSATION ENGINE
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Gemini Flash does TWO things: structured extraction + conversational response.

## Thing 1: Context extraction
Customer types: "My mom Linda is visiting from Florida, she can't have gluten.
Jake has a summer cold. Saturday we're doing a BBQ. It's going to be super hot."

LLM extracts JSON:
{
  "household_changes": [{"action": "add_temp", "name": "Linda", "conditions": ["celiac"]}],
  "health_states": [{"member": "Jake", "condition": "cold", "since": "today"}],
  "dietary_needs": [{"date": "Saturday", "requirement": "bbq", "constraints": []}],
  "mood": {"overall": "light_fresh", "reason": "hot_weather"},
  "practical_needs": []
}

## Thing 2: Conversational response
Warm, uses member names and American product names (kale, Greek yogurt, quinoa).

Prompt must handle:
- English and Spanish (e.g. "Solo esta semana somos dos...")
- US cultural context: Thanksgiving, BBQ, meal prep Sunday, keto, paleo, July 4th,
  Super Bowl party, potluck, tailgate
- Implicit references: "the kid" → Jake, "grandma" → Linda
- Corrections: "Actually Jake is feeling better" → remove cold state
- American food names in responses — NOT Indian names (kale not palak, lentils not dal)

Remove: puja, sattvic, Ekadashi, sabzi mandi, Hinglish/Telugu examples.

Store in lib/ai.ts. Use @google/generative-ai SDK.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 10. BASKET OPTIMIZER
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Algorithm unchanged. US example output:
{
  items: [...],
  coverageScore: 87,
  perMemberCoverage: {Mike: 82, Sarah: 94, Jake: 91, Linda: 78},
  totalPrice: 84.50,
  weeklyContext: "BBQ Saturday, Jake has cold, Linda visiting gluten-free"
}

Store in lib/optimizer.ts.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 11. FRONTEND RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

Design system: same tokens as Section 1. Mobile-first, desktop-polished for judges.

Key pages unchanged in structure. Display rules:
- Currency: $X,XXX.XX (US format) — NOT ₹
- Product names: English only in UI (nameTe not displayed)
- Nutrition from USDA FoodData Central (not IFCT)
- Product detail: USDA nutrition per 100g, health badge with member names

Chat panel transforms shop page behind it — same UX as before.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 12. CODING STANDARDS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

- TypeScript strict mode. No `any` types.
- Server Components by default. Client Components only for interactivity.
- Prisma for all database queries. No raw SQL in application code.
- API format: { data: {...} } or { error: { message: "..." } }
- All prices in USD. Format as $X,XXX.XX
- Times in local US timezone for display (or user's browser locale)
- Product names: English only in UI
- Component files: PascalCase.tsx. Utility files: camelCase.ts.

Ponytail philosophy: minimum code, reuse before rewrite, never skip validation/types.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 13. WHAT NOT TO DO
# ─────────────────────────────────────────

- Do NOT build auth, payments, admin panel, or notifications
- Do NOT use Redis, Docker, or infrastructure beyond Aurora + Vercel
- Do NOT use placeholder data
- Do NOT make the LLM score products
- Do NOT build a recipe recommender
- Do NOT skip commits
- Do NOT use localStorage for family data
- Do NOT install UI component libraries (no shadcn, no MUI)
- Do NOT over-engineer

